## Triage Check: Which of the "Three Blockers" Actually Blocks?

I agree with your triage in structure but disagree on one severity assignment.

| Blocker | Blocker Severity | Minimum Viable Fix | Cost to Fix |
|---|---|---|---|
| COI disclosure | **Hard block.** One hostile tweet sinks the vote. | One paragraph + recusal rule. Daniel's curator status disclosed *as a feature*, not hidden. | ~30 min |
| Day-1 OSS commitment | **Medium block.** Sophisticated voters will ask; won't sink alone. | Change "upon delivery" → "from Month 1." Create public repo. | ~1 hour |
| LOI / ecosystem demand | **Hard block + team-capability signal.** Underweighted in your triage. | One LOI from any named curator. | 1 day of email |

**On LOI severity — the non-obvious point:**

LOIs have now been requested three times: v0.1 review, meeting feedback, v0.3 debate. Still absent in v0.4. Daniel's reportedly-existing list (Steakhouse, Gauntlet, Re7, Rockaway) makes this more concerning, not less. The repeated non-delivery is one of three things:

1. **They asked and got declines** → thesis is weaker than the draft implies
2. **They haven't asked** → judgment or prioritization problem
3. **They're banking them for launch** → tactically wrong; LOIs belong in the governance forum thread, not the marketing push

Every option is a team-execution signal. A Morpho governance voter who reads the v0.3 debate and notices that the third request went unaddressed will (correctly) update on team responsiveness. **This matters more than the document gap itself.** The LOI isn't just a missing artifact; it's the test case for whether this team closes loops.

