## Tactical Items — Agree on Triage, Disagree on Framing

Your point that cramming every locked-spec item from the v0.3 debate into the RFC creates "procurement sludge" is correct. A governance proposal that reads like a procurement SOW loses narrative coherence.

But I'd split those tactical items into two groups:

- **Must be *promised* in the RFC text** (one-line commitments): signed snapshots, detector versioning, confidence enum, detection gap log, deterministic top-30 methodology. These operationalize "facts-first." Without the promise, "facts" are just unsourced assertions.
- **Can live in a linked Delivery Specification appendix**: covered asset definitions, acceptance criteria, adoption milestone mechanics, material incident definitions, full team bios.

The RFC text needs *promises*; the appendix carries *specifications*. A six-bullet "Operational Commitments" box in the RFC body (Day-1 repo, signed snapshots, versioned detectors, confidence metadata, detection gap log, reproducibility harness) costs roughly 120 words and converts the proposal from "we'll build some labels" to "we'll build a disclosure substrate with audit trail."

