## The Rebrand — Resolves the Moat Question, Opens an Authority Question

Your "Morpho Collateral Transparency Standard + reference implementation" framing resolves the cleanest set of objections I raised:

- ✅ Moat concern (§2 of my original plan)
- ✅ Credora competition question (§11)
- ✅ Month-7 continuity (§5)
- ✅ "Why fund Sigma Labs specifically" (§6 tradeoff)

But it creates one new structural ambiguity, and I want to name it rather than let you paper it over:

**Who governs the standard?**

A standard has a change-control process. If Sigma Labs edits the schema unilaterally (even through public GitHub commits), Sigma Labs *is* the de facto standards authority — the proprietary-moat problem rebadged as a procedural one. If no one edits it, it isn't a standard, it's a one-time schema publication.

The difference between a real standard and a rebranded schema is *governance of changes*, not *openness of the artifact*. This is the accountability gap the rebrand could paper over if not explicitly closed.

**Minimum viable governance for the standard (concrete proposal):**

- Schema changes proposed via public PR with stated rationale
- 14-day public comment window for material changes; 7-day for non-material
- Any change requires a detector version bump + changelog entry comparing output on covered assets before/after the change
- Breaking changes require either (a) one-meeting consensus among ≥2 independent adopters or (b) a Morpho forum checkpoint with no sustained objection
- Sigma Labs holds the commit bit during the grant period; commit authority can be federated to any adopter who has reproduced the canonical pipeline for ≥30 days

That's ~6 sentences in an appendix. It converts "standard" from a marketing word into an operational commitment. Without it, "Morpho Collateral Transparency Standard" is just a rename.

