## 5. Governance-Integration Rationale Paragraph

New section, placed immediately after **Prior Art: Credora by RedStone** and before **What this grant delivers**.

> **Relationship to the Morpho Protocol**
>
> This grant funds a public disclosure substrate. Sigma Labs is not requesting Morpho to endorse a risk model, grant Sigma Labs parameter-setting authority, or commit the Morpho interface to displaying registry outputs. None of these are in scope, and none are implied by funding.
>
> The rationale for sponsoring the substrate from the Morpho treasury is threefold. First, the top 30 Morpho vaults are the substrate's initial coverage set; curator transparency is a protocol-level interest as much as a depositor interest. Second, a reproducible, open disclosure layer reduces the concentration of collateral-risk knowledge in closed-source vendors — an industry-wide concern made acute by the Chaos Labs departure from Aave in April 2026 and the parallel shift toward protocol-owned risk infrastructure. Third, the artifact is available to every participant — Morpho, curators, depositors, insurers, third-party risk providers, independent researchers — on equal terms, with no vendor gatekeeping.
>
> Whether Morpho subsequently integrates registry outputs into app.morpho.org, governance tooling, or any other interface is a separate decision for Morpho governance to make after Phase 1 delivery, on the basis of the artifacts produced. This RFC presumes no such integration and requests no commitment to it.

